        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0dc350c5011d7706",
        "text": "\nNew Babylon, [no date]. Versobooks.com. Online. [Accessed 18 January 2023]. Available from: https://www.versobooks.com/blogs/1879-new-babylonIf there was a high point for the radical imagination of a future for the planet, perhaps it was Constant Nieuwenhuys’ New Babylon. Constant was a key member of the Situationist International in its early phase. He started work on New Babylon before he resigned from it, and continued working on it for many years. It embodied many of the situationosts’ key ideas about constructing situations for permanent play, but here imagined at the scale of an infrastructure for a planetery utopia dedicated to nomadic play. Here’s a few extracts from my book The Beach Beneath the Street about this amazing work.  New Babylon  Constant built a future out of offcut plexiglass and bicycle spokes.  Later he would say that his marvelous models of New Babylon were appreciated in much the same way as African masks were in surrealist times, as interesting forms, but stripped of their magical significance. What is lost from New Babylon is a passion gone from the world, a desire to seize the world itself as the object of desire, to find a form for the whole of life.\n"
